Part I - Ford GoBike Data exploration¶

by KADI Amir Khalid¶

Introduction¶

Ford GoBike System Data: This data set includes information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area with +180k instances.

df1['start_hour'] = df1['start_time'].dt.hour

# Filter only the trips that happened during the day (between 6am and 9pm)
df1 = df1[(df1['start_hour'] >= 6) & (df1['start_hour'] <= 21)]

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The Ford GoBike System Data is a CSV (comma-separated values) file that contains trip data for the Ford GoBike bike-sharing service. The dataset contains 16 columns and over 180k rows of data. Here is a brief description of each column in the dataset:

  • duration_sec: the duration of the trip in seconds
  • start_time: the date and time when the trip started
  • end_time: the date and time when the trip ended
  • start_station_id: the ID of the starting station
  • start_station_name: the name of the starting station
  • start_station_latitude: the latitude of the starting station
  • start_station_longitude: the longitude of the starting station
  • end_station_id: the ID of the ending station
  • end_station_name: the name of the ending station
  • end_station_latitude: the latitude of the ending station
  • end_station_longitude: the longitude of the ending station
  • bike_id: the ID of the bike used for the trip
  • user_type: the type of user (subscriber or customer)
  • member_birth_year: the birth year of the user (if available)
  • member_gender: the gender of the user (if available)
  • bike_share_for_all_trip: whether the user was enrolled in the Bike Share for All program for low-income residents

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

Trip duration: this feature can provide insights into how long users typically ride the bikes, which can inform decisions around bike availability, pricing, and user satisfaction.

User demographics: features such as user type (e.g. customer vs. subscriber), gender, and age can help understand who is using the bike-sharing service and whether there are any differences in usage patterns or preferences between different user groups.

Most popular stations: features such as start_station_name can help to answer this question

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

For the trip duration question features such as (duration_sec, start_time, end_time) can help to answer this quetion

For User demographics: features such as user_type, member_gender, member_birth_year, and bike_share_for_all_trip can provide insights into user demographics and preferences. For example, analyzing the distribution of user types can help understand the proportion of subscribers vs. one-time customers using the bike-sharing service, while analyzing the distribution of gender and age can help identify any patterns or differences in usage between different user groups.

For Most popular stations features such as start_station could help to answer this answer and demonstrate how the instances are distributed

def count_plot(df1,x,default_color,xlabel,ylabel,title):
    # Create the countplot using seaborn
    sb.countplot(data=df1, x=x,color=default_color,order=df1[x].value_counts().index)

    # Set the plot labels
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    plt.title(title)

    # Show the plot
    plt.show()

def bar_plot(df1,x_groupby,default_color,xlabel,ylabel,title):
    station_counts = df1.groupby(x_groupby).size().reset_index(name='count')
    # Sort the results in descending order and select the top 10 stations
    top_stations = station_counts.sort_values(by='count', ascending=False).head(10)
    plt.figure(figsize=(15, 10))

    # Create the bar plot using seaborn
    sb.barplot(data=top_stations, y=x_groupby, x='count',color=default_color)

    # Set the plot labels
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.title(title)

    # Show the plot
    plt.show()

# there's a long tail in the distribution, so let's put it on a log scale instead

plt.figure(figsize=[8, 5])
plt.hist(data = df1, x = 'duration_sec', bins = bins)
plt.xscale('log')
plt.xticks([100,250,500, 1e3, 2e3, 5e3, 1e4, 2e4], [100,250,500, '1k', '2k', '5k', '10k', '20k'])
plt.xlabel('Trip Duration (seconds)')

We can notice that the most of distribution of trip duration is between 300 sec and 1500 sec, alghou there are some outliers that pass 10k seconds

df1['start_week_day'] = df1['start_time'].dt.day_name()

# convert cut, color, and clarity into ordered categorical types
ordinal_var = {'start_week_day': ['Monday','Tuesday','Wednesday','Thursday','Friday','Saturday','Sunday']}


ordinal_type = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered = True,
                                                categories = ordinal_var['start_week_day'])
df1['start_week_day'] = df1['start_week_day'].astype(ordinal_type)
plt.figure(figsize=[8,5])
sb.countplot(data=df1, x='start_week_day', color=sb.color_palette()[0])

plt.ylabel('Count')
plt.title('Number of Trips by Day of Week')
plt.show()

It seems that in the weekend there is less trips than the rest of the week, this might be cause by the fact that the trips are not all the time for fun or hanging around the city.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

  • Trips are less during the weekend, in order to get this conclusion I had to add new column start_week_day for the trip day name extracted from start_time column
  • Trip Duration high distribution is located between 300sec and 1500sec, in order to get this conclusion I had to use a log scale because it seems there are some outliers that reach gigh duration like +20000 seconds equivalent to + 5 hours
  • Midday start hours are less popular
  • Most of the trips are made by males
  • Most of the members are of age between 26 and 35, in order to get this conclusion I had to add new column for member_age_range using member_age column

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

Added new columns start_hour start_week_day for the trip start hour and trip start day
I had to use log scale to see the distribution of trips using trip duration

In [23]:
# Calculate the first and third quartiles of duration_sec
q1 = df1["duration_sec"].quantile(0.25)
q3 = df1["duration_sec"].quantile(0.75)

# Calculate the IQR of duration_sec
iqr = q3 - q1

# Define the lower and upper bounds for outliers
lower_bound = q1 - 1.5 * iqr
upper_bound = q3 + 1.5 * iqr

# Filter out the outliers of duration_sec
df2 = df1[(df1["duration_sec"] >= lower_bound) & (df1["duration_sec"] <= upper_bound)]

In terms of the Ford GoBike System Data, the "Subscriber" user type refers to users who have purchased a bike sharing membership, while the "Customer" user type refers to users who have rented a bike without purchasing a membership.

bike_share_for_all_trip is a column in the Ford GoBike System dataset that indicates whether the user who took the trip was enrolled in the "Bike Share for All" program. This program is designed to provide low-income residents with affordable access to bike share systems in order to promote transportation equity. Users who are enrolled in this program may have different usage patterns or trip characteristics compared to users who are not enrolled.

Conclusions¶

my investigation of Ford GoBike System Data had lead me to the following conclusions:

  • Trips are less during the weekend
  • Trip Duration high distribution is located between 300sec and 1500sec,
  • Midday start hours are less popular
  • Most of the trips are made by males
  • Most of the members are of age between 26 and 35
  • Start Latitude and End Longitude have a high correlation, but this information cannot lead into further insights unless using geographic analysis
  • Most of the subscribers are males, same for customers and for the bike sharing for all trip because males are the majority of members
  • Females have the highest mean trip duration during all the Hours of day
  • Mean age decreases in the weekends and the end of the day for both user types
  • Customer type has higher mean trip duration during all the hours of the day than subscriber type
  • Mean duration for Customer increases in weekends
